'''Gay Hendricks''' (born 1945 in [[Leesburg, Florida]]) is a psychologist, writer, and teacher in the field of [[personal growth]], relationships, and body intelligence.<ref>[http://www.liberation2010.com/speakers/gay.html# Hendricks as keynote speaker at Liberation 2010 conference] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091031100418/http://www.liberation2010.com/speakers/gay.html |date=2009-10-31 }}</ref> He is best known for his work in relationship enhancement and in the development of [[conscious breathing]] exercises.<ref>[http://www.amsa.org/healingthehealer/breathing.cfm American Medical Student Association book recommendation] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100130092432/http://www.amsa.org/healingthehealer/breathing.cfm |date=2010-01-30 }}</ref>
After receiving his Ph.D. in psychology from [[Stanford University]] in 1974, Gay began teaching at the [[University of Colorado at Boulder|University of Colorado]]. He spent 21 years at the University of Colorado and became a Full Professor in the Counseling Psychology Department while founding '''The Hendricks Institute'''.<ref>''Conscious Breathing'', Bantam Books, 1995 {{ISBN|978-0-553-37443-8}} (about the author)</ref> He conducts workshops with his wife of more than 33 years, Dr. Kathlyn Hendricks. Together they have authored over 35 books. They have appeared on numerous radio and television shows, including an interview with radio host [[Jean Chatzky]].<ref name="Chatzky">{{cite web|url=http://www.oprah.com/oprahradio/Taking-the-Big-Leap-Audio|title=Taking the Big Leap|last=Chatzky|first=Jean|date=May 14, 2009|work=[[Oprah Radio]]|accessdate=24 July 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131224105944/http://www.oprah.com/oprahradio/Taking-the-Big-Leap-Audio|archivedate=2013-12-24}}</ref>

Hendricks co-founded The Spiritual Cinema Circle with his wife and producer Stephen Simon, and was Executive Producer for the film ''[[Zen Noir]]'' (2004).<ref>[https://movies.nytimes.com/person/491119/Gay-Hendricks New York Times Movie & TV biographies]</ref> He served as producer and writer on the [[Louise Hay]] movie, ''[[You Can Heal Your Life]]''. In 2011, he partnered with writer Tinker Lindsey to begin the Tenzing Zorbu mystery series, with titles such as ''The First Rule of Ten'' and ''The Second Rule of Ten'', which illustrate emotional and spiritual challenges in the life of a fictional ex-monk private detective. A short biopic was made of his life for Polish television, wherein he was portrayed by Canadian actor, Jon Cubbon.

