{{Infobox medical condition | name = {{PAGENAME}} | synonyms = VEOIBD | image = | alt = | caption = | pronounce = | field = | ICD10 = <!--{{ICD10|Xxx.x}}--> | ICD9 = <!--{{ICD9|xxx}}--> | ICDO = | OMIM = | DiseasesDB = | MedlinePlus = | eMedicineSubj = | eMedicineTopic = | MeSH = | GeneReviewsNBK = | GeneReviewsName = | Orphanet = }}
Very early onset [[inflammatory bowel disease]] (VEOIBD) is a type of [[Inflammatory bowel disease|IBD]] which starts in people younger than 6 years of age. According to age we can distiguish more specifically two categories within the VEOIBD diagnosis - naonatal [[Inflammatory bowel disease|IBD]] (patients younger than 1 month) and infantile [[Inflammatory bowel disease|IBD]] (patients younger than 2 years old).<ref name=":0">{{Cite journal|last=Uhlig|first=Holm H.|last2=Schwerd|first2=Tobias|last3=Koletzko|first3=Sibylle|last4=Shah|first4=Neil|last5=Kammermeier|first5=Jochen|last6=Elkadri|first6=Abdul|last7=Ouahed|first7=Jodie|last8=Wilson|first8=David C.|last9=Travis|first9=Simon P.|date=2014-11|title=The Diagnostic Approach to Monogenic Very Early Onset Inflammatory Bowel Disease|url=https://dx.doi.org/10.1053/j.gastro.2014.07.023|journal=Gastroenterology|volume=147|issue=5|pages=990–1007.e3|doi=10.1053/j.gastro.2014.07.023|issn=0016-5085|pmc=5376484|pmid=25058236}}</ref>
== Signs and symptoms == VEIOBD patients present with severe form of the disease that responds poorly to conventional therapies. The symptoms often include not only gastrointestinal tract, but also other tissues, such as [[pituitary gland]], [[spleen]], [[liver]], [[skin]], [[respiratory tract]] or [[blood]].<ref name=":0" />
On the other hand, other types of [[primary immunodeficiency]] can often manifest with IBD-like symptoms, too. These include the [[IPEX syndrome]], [[Wiskott–Aldrich syndrome|Wiskott-Aldrich syndrome]], [[XIAP syndrome]] or [[chronic granulomatous disease]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1007/978-3-319-49215-5_5|title=Pediatric Inflammatory Bowel Disease|last=Kelsen|first=Judith|last2=Sullivan|first2=Kathleen|date=2017|publisher=Springer, Cham|isbn=9783319492131|pages=55–67|language=en|doi=10.1007/978-3-319-49215-5_5}}</ref>
== Causes == [[Inflammatory bowel disease|Inflammatory bowel diseases]] (IBDs), such as [[Crohn's disease|Crohn Disease]] (CD) or [[Ulcerative colitis|Ulcerative Colitis]] (UC), are chronic inflammatory conditions of the [[gastrointestinal tract]]. Up-to-date findings show that the pathogenesis is influenced by both environmental and genetic factors. A considerable number of [[Monogenic (genetics)|monogenic]] disorders can be found especially among patients with VEOIBD. Causal mutations can be found in genes involved in epithelial barrier formation ([[COL7A1]], [[FERMT1]]), [[Innate immune system|innate]] ([[CYBB]], [[G6PC3]]), as well as the [[specific immune response]] and immune regulation ([[IL10 (gene)|IL10]], [[Interleukin 10 receptor, alpha subunit|IL10RA]], [[FOXP3]]).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Uhlig|first=Holm H.|date=2013-12-01|title=Monogenic diseases associated with intestinal inflammation: implications for the understanding of inflammatory bowel disease|url=http://gut.bmj.com/content/62/12/1795|journal=Gut|language=en|volume=62|issue=12|pages=1795–1805|doi=10.1136/gutjnl-2012-303956|issn=0017-5749|pmid=24203055}}</ref>
